In the case of the Camera device, all of the information that is currently stored
as attributes to the device is also being stored in this field (since this is
really where it belongs).  The NIST imaging software will pull all camera info
from this connection table field rather than the device attributes.  The device
attributes will currently be left in place for backwards compatability.

message.raw:
Added a new update mode to the novatech DDS9m.

Now with the update_mode='asynchronous' instantiation argument, the novatech can
be used with an ordinary clocking source - it will load the next value of its
table on each falling edge and update its output asynchonously within the next
100us. This currenly results in incorrect output, and requires the PulseBlaster
to produce shorter clock pulses to make it more accurate. This is because, since
the novatech updates on the falling edge, the falling edge needs to be soon after
a rising edge if we are to minimise inaccuracy from this.

In the present implementation the falling edge can be arbitrarily late, making
this mode of operation unreliable (well, more unreliable than the 100us of delay
it gives regardless).

be used with an ordinary clocking source - it will load the next value of its
table on each falling edge and update its output asynchonously within the next
100us. This currenly results in incorrect output, and requires the PulseBlaster
to produce shorter clock pulses to make it more accurate. This is because, since
the novatech updates on the falling edge, the falling edge needs to be soon after
a rising edge if we are to minimise inaccuracy from this.

In the present implementation the falling edge can be arbitrarily late, making
this mode of operation unreliable (well, more unreliable than the 100us of delay
it gives regardless).

message.raw:
reverted the majority of the regression fix in commit: 58ad2e1ecf9c to fix further regressions introduced.

This regression fix appears to be mostly wrong. The static channel values stored in the HDF5 file were not quantised correctly.
This resulted in the static DDS channels being programmed with 0 amplitude and the frequency was out by a factor of 10.
The bug was actually introduced by incorrectly accessing the DDS sub-channel output values through the static_value parameter.
At the generate_code stage of the experiment, you should be accessing the raw_output array (as you cannot, by design, modify the contents of the static_value which is what you mean to do when you quantise the output)

Likely the original fix was introduced because of exceptions raised when compiling an experiment where a StaticDDS was not explictly commanded to set it's output. In such an instance it would fall back on the default value. The default value for Static(Analog/Digital)Quantities were not placed in the raw_output array correctly. This regression was fixed in a commit to the labscript repo: 7e50a2a0ce06

message.raw:
Lots of refactoring of DDSs.

DDSs had many references to specific classes for their parent devices, and their behaviour was
slightly different depending on what parent device they had. This has been solved in a few ways.

For DDSs attached to a PhaseMatrixQuickSyn, there is now a subclass of DDS,
labscript_utils.PhaseMatrixQuickSyn.QuickSynDDS, which supports only frequency
control and only static gating.

For Novatechs, one should still use DDS and StaticDDS, but they call methods on
the parents asking questions about how to initialise, such as whether a certain
unit conversion class should be used if the user hasn't specified one. If the parent
does not implement this method get_default_unit_conversion_classes(), it is ignored,
so this is backward compatible.

For PulseBlasters, DDS is also still the class to use, however the creation of a
DigitalQuantity for its gating is now done in the PulseBlaster's add_device method.

In order to facilitate this, Device.__init__ now takes an argument call_parents_add_device,
which, if set to false, means Device.__init__ will not call parent_device.add_device.

This allows subclasses more control over when parent_device.add_device is called
in their own __init__ method, although it remains the case that they *must* call it
at some point in their __init__ method if they tell Device.__init__ not to.

This commit corresponds to a simultaneous one in the labscript module which
implements part of this change.
